snippet.textDisplay: Hey Les, so this is my birth story. I was in an induced labor for 35 hours before being scheduled for an emergency c section. I was given an epidural and my daughter was being pulled out of me, in what felt like 15 minutes. She was pronounced born at 12:37pm December 30, 2015. They handed her to me for skin to skin but I had this uneasy feeling overtake my body and I asked they had her to my husband. I then sort of passed out and could only hear the nurse telling me not to fall asleep. She was hitting my cheek lightly to wake me up too. It was a weird feeling. I thought my eyes were open but everything was white and it felt very warm. I suddenly started to throw up and realized my eyes had been closed the whole time and realized I was still in the emergency room and the nurse yelled “she’s awake! Stay with me honey!” Literally one of the weirdest feelings I’ve experienced. I was cleaned up and wheeled out and my baby was waiting for me with my husband. I was able to do skin to skin immediately but I was so tired. She had a scar on her face also that I was told from the umbilical cord wrapped around her neck but I believe the doctor lied to me about that. I believe it was from the doctor pulling her out with the tool he used. I regret so much now not being more upset over that and taking his word. But in the end I have a healthy intelligent daughter that we both could not be more proud of. She has no scaring visible and she’s really just the light in our lives. I’m so excited for you Leslie.♥️ your own journey through motherhood is a precious journey, enjoy it all. The good and bad and remember in moments you feel like you’re not giving enough or putting your all, know that you are. And no matter what is happening in the world, you are the world to your child. Welcome to the best hood! #motherhood

snippet.textDisplay: I had two natural births and my last baby was an unexpected c section. We decided it was the safest due to some bleeding and we didn’t want to try natural even though it was possible but I didn’t really want to risk anything happening and end up having it be an emergency c section. Point is I was super scared of having a c section I cried as they prepared me for the operation because I was super nervous but I knew it was best. Now I am 2 months postpartum and looking back I’m glad I had a c section because it was definitely the easiest labor out of the 3 considering that I ripped with both of them and I didn’t have an epidural. In case you do have a c section just prepare yourself mentally. The first week is hard but it gets better I promise you that. There are definitely pros and cons with going natural and a c section but at the end of the day whatever is safest for baby and yourself is what really matters and I hope it all works out for you ❤️

snippet.textDisplay:
Most of my pregnancy I would get so dehydrated I had to go to the ER. I would go in thinking I was in labor and I never was, towards the end I was like screw it I’ll just wait for my water to break. I went to my last doctors apt and was 2cm dialated and 70% effaced. I scheduled to be induced on September 27th (my oldest daughters birthday is September 27th of 2016) so I thought to myself yay I’ll have both my girls birthdays on the same day I was so excited. On Sep 26th I got the worst contractions ever, I waited them out until I couldn’t handle it anymore, I gave birth to my babygirl Sep 26th of 2019. Just a few hours and my girls would have had the same birthday! ☹️ lol
You never know you may or may not go into labor before your induction, you’ll know when your in actual labor, you’ll feel it. I hope you have a safe delivery, whatever it may be, natural or c-section, just as long as you and baby are healthy. Good luck!
